    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_447685579" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/447685579" />
    <a title="Danielle" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/784513-danielle"><img alt="Danielle" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1220889844p2/784513.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/447685579?book_show_action=true">Nov 03, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Danielle" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Danielle" href="/user/show/784513-danielle">Danielle</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/784513-danielle?shelf=danielle-recommends">danielle-recommends</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/784513-danielle?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer447685579" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10070168487482131584">I actually checked this out from the library for my husband, thinking it would be the kind of (lame) thing he would like. But, I ended up reading it myself and totally loved it. It covers an era and location in history that just doesn&apos;t get much play, and I was very impressed with the author&apos;s ability to cover a big subject in a way that was cohesive, interesting, and kept moving. Good non-fiction is an art, people.<br/>Anyway, from the title, I thought this was mostly going to be about war. Indian a</span>
  <span id="freeText10070168487482131584" style="display:none">I actually checked this out from the library for my husband, thinking it would be the kind of (lame) thing he would like. But, I ended up reading it myself and totally loved it. It covers an era and location in history that just doesn't get much play, and I was very impressed with the author's ability to cover a big subject in a way that was cohesive, interesting, and kept moving. Good non-fiction is an art, people.<br />Anyway, from the title, I thought this was mostly going to be about war. Indian and Mexican wars in the American Southwest. And, it was, but it was much more about the people who made the Southwest what it was (namely Kit Carson. I can't believe he's not mentioned anywhere in the title or subtitle of this book, because this is basically an expanded biography of Kit Carson. Who, by the way, never robbed a bank. I think I was getting him mixed up with...well, I'm thinking of Kit Carson and the Sundance Kid, but I know that's not right. Who goes with the Sundance Kid? Also, is the Sundance Kid real? Unfortunately, this book didn't talk about bank robbers, or stage coach robbers, or any kind of Wild West robbers, so I'm still a little murky on that subject.) ANYWAY, what this book DID cover was very interesting. It details the events in the American West and Southwest over a period of at least three decades, so "epic" is an accurate description. <br />One thing I liked about it was that it helped me understand what was happening elsewhere in the West during the time the Mormon pioneers were travelling to and settling Utah. This book doesn't talk about the Mormons much (which is fine, since I already know our history pretty well), but it DID talk about everyone else around these parts (which is, spoiler: not that many people) during that same time period. I also liked getting to know the different American Indian tribes and what happened to them. It's really surprising that so much of this history is unknown to most Americans. Anyway, if you've got a lot of time to kill, or a profound interest in history, Native Americans, and/or the Southwest, I very much recommend this book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10070168487482131584" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

